Hi everyone. I&#39;m a founding member of the Spokane Paranormal Society and the
caretaker of Lakeview Cemetery in Sprague, Washington.



On the issue of hearing what someone says it is, I&#39;d like to call attention
to the issue of misheard lyrics, a similar phenomenon. For example, in the
song &quot;Every Breath You Take&quot; by the Police, does Sting sing &quot;I&#39;m a pool hall
ace&quot; or &quot;How my poor heart aches&quot;? The second is correct, but many people
hear the first. Then, once you know what it really says, you can then hear
the correct lyrics on playback.



There is no lyric sheet to refer to with EVP and the answers can be tricky
unless the recording is unusually clear, which is the exception. Everything
else is interpretation. Having multiple people listen to a recording without
being given an interpretation to listen for and then tallying the consensus
is probably the best way to decide what an EVP is likely saying, and even
then, there is still usually room for competing possibilities.



As to what type of entity provides the recording, all the answers are purely
speculation. I choose to accept ghosts as the usual suspects in EVP
recordings but even that could be my own predisposition masquerading as
objectivity. Depends on who you ask. Your mileage may vary.



I just did a one hour EVP session tonight at the cemetery with the SPS team.
I plan to play it back tomorrow. If I got anything worth repeating, I&#39;ll
post about it. One team member heard a small girl humming. Hopefully that
ended up on someone&#39;s recorder.



EVP is an endlessly fascinating subject!



Michael Breckenridge



From: EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com [mailto:EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com] On Behalf Of
rasterer
