Subject: [EVP-ITC] Re: I am new here





Hello Alan. I guess &#39;testing&#39; starts with what you believe is beyond
question or cannot be tested, and what you believe should be questioned and
can be tested. Different people believe EVPs fall in different places on
that spectrum of possibilities, and there are different opinions on what the
voices heard are (afterlife? aliens? angels? pareidolia? radio programs?
something else?)

If you wanted to go back to first principles, you could first examine where
you fall on that list, and then determine what tests you could perform to
confirm or dispute that belief. For example, if you believe the voices are
from aliens, it might first be good to determine how you know aliens exist,
since if you can&#39;t do even that, the value of the belief the voices are from
aliens, seems to drop alot.

Or, if you are already convinced aliens exist and the voices are from
aliens, you could always try testing their accuracy. For example, getting
dates and very clear predictions, or answers to questions you can confirm,
and go from there. I would avoid yes/no questions, and multiple choice
questions, since that can predispose you to hearing certain answers.

Another tricky thing, is that these often are not clear voices. I have seen
instances where what one person hears is not what another person hears,
which can make it hard to be sure if you are interpreting the sound
correctly. Further, I have seen where a person will listen to a recording,
not know what it is, then be told what it is, and only then can they hear
it. So if you are trying to determine what a voice is saying, and you get
someone else to listen but you first tell them what it says, they might then
hear it when otherwise they would not. So again, for the most objective
testing there, listen to sounds (or have others listen to them) without
first being told what it is supposed to be saying. And using a second person
like this can also help to lessen the possibility you are hearing what you
want to hear.

Of course, if you are not interested in testing, that is also your decision.
Many people do not do any testing: they just make recordings, label them
what they think they say, and upload them to show others. 

Good luck with it.

